See above, [_Sect._ vi. _Art._ 1, 2.]

{#n2}
See [_Sect._ iii. _Art._ 11, 12.]

{#n3}
See [_Sect._ iii. _Art._ 15. _Par._ 3.]

{#n4}
See [_Sect._ 3. _Art._ ix.] _The Author all along supposes, that no Man acts without some _Desire_, or _Instinct_, or _Affection_, or _Appetite_; that of these _Attachments_ of the Will, some are calm and unpassionate, others are passionate; some are extensive, and others confined to one, or to a few. The former Sort in each of these Divisions, manifestly appears more amiable; and consequently, $caeteris paribus$, the Virtue is less, in any given Quanity of Good done from the violent, passionate, and narrow Attachment. A certain _Remarker_ thence argues, "That then the Virtue is highest, when there is no Desire, Affection, or Attachment at all; or when we act solely from Reason, without any _Affection_ to any Thing." One may retort this Reasoning in a like Case. In any given _Momentum_ of Bodies, there the _Velocity_ is greater, where there is least _Matter_; consequently, it is there greatest, where there is no _Matter_ at all._

{#n5}
See [_Art._ 10. _Par._ 6. _of this Section_.]

